for $Î¸_j = Ï€(j-1/2)/n$. Prove that $C_n$ is orthogonal: $C_n^âŠ¤ C_n = C_n C_n^âŠ¤ = I$.
Hint: $C_n C_n^âŠ¤ = I$ might be easier to show than $C_n^âŠ¤ C_n = I$ using the previous problem.

**SOLUTION**

The components of $C$ without the diagonal matrix, which we may call $\hat{C}$ are
$$
\hat{C}_{ij} = \cos((j-1)Î¸_{i-1}),
$$
where $Î¸_j = Ï€(j-1/2)/n$. Recalling that the elements of matrix multiplication are given by
$$
(ab)_{ij} := \sum_{k=1}^n a_{ik} b_{kj}
$$
we find that
$$
(\hat{C}_n \hat{C}_n^âŠ¤)_{ij} = \sum_{k=1}^n \cos((i-1)Î¸_{k-1}) \cos((k-1)Î¸_{j-1}).
$$

By using the previous problem and the terms on the diagonal matrices which ensure that the $1/2$ terms become $1$ we know how to compute all of these entries and find that it is the identity.

